  "source_test": "HEC.FDA.ModelTest/unittests/structures/StructureShould.cs (ComputeStructureDamage, SELA_StructureDamage_Should)",
  "note": "construct is {occupancy_type: {name, damage_category, struct_depths, struct_damages:[{type,params}], content_depths, content_damages:[{type,params}], ffe:{dist,std_or_min,[central],[max]}, structure_value:{dist,std_or_min,[max]}, csvr:{dist,std_or_min,central,[max]}}, sample:[iteration, computeIsDeterministic], structure:{fid, first_floor_elevation, val_struct, st_damcat, occtype, impact_area_id, [val_cont], [val_vehic], [val_other], [ground_elevation]}}. Unlike structures/occupancy_type.json (which shares one 'depths' array between struct/content), struct_depths/content_depths are separate here because the SELA case's structure and content depth-percent-damage curves have different lengths (21 vs 18 points) -- a bespoke schema for this bespoke 'structure' dispatch target, not a reuse of the occupancy_type dispatch. Each assertion builds the occupancy type + structure fresh, samples once, and dispatches compute_damage_{struct,content,vehicle,other} = the four tuple items of Structure::compute_damage(wse, sampled, priceIndex=1, analysisYear=9999); 'args' is [wse]. The 'compute_structure_damage' case reproduces ComputeStructureDamage's shared fixture (Normal depth-percent-damage curves, CSVR-driven content); the 'sela_structure_*' cases reproduce SELA_StructureDamage_Should's triangular occupancy type against two real SELA structures. All expected values gate-pinned ('PIN'); the rounded literals in each case's note are the upstream InlineData/computed cross-check values, not hand-derived oracle values.",
